text:
On tap, poured a clear yellow hue w/ medium lasting white frothy head and thick lacing. Moderate bready aromas. Initial flavor is light sweet w/ a moderate bitter finish. Tastes are crackers, white bread, and grassy hops. Light bodied and lively carbonation w/ a creamy mouthfeel.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

50cl mug draft at Prost Brewing Company in Denver, Colorado. The pour is slight haze golden with a well formed one inch white head. Nice lace left behind on the glass. The aroma is earth, herbal and fresh cracker malt. The taste is really nice herbal clove, mineral, fresh hay and the bready cracker malt. The palate is light bodied with soft natural carbonation, mineral clean, lingering clove finish. Really nice Keller beer.
Pours clear gold with small white head. Notes of hay, straw, spice, banana and creamy fruit. Light bodied. Enjoyable
Draught at the brewery. Low fluffy lasting white head. Clear yellow golden body. Mild grass straw aroma and flavor, little hops bitterness, long finish.

Tap at the brewery. Hazy gold with a tall, fine head. Nice hop nose, lemony, floral. Biscuity malt. Crisp, hoppy flavor with a good malt backbone. Great stuff. Wish I had ordered a mass. Their best beer, and a top quality American kellerbier.
On tap, hazy almost clear golden color, nice white froth, aroma and flavor has a good balance of hops , grainy corn mash, balanced clean finish

Clear gold, great bready honey nose. Clean crackery malts with a crisp herbal hop bitterness.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

On tap at Colorado Plus poured a clear yellow with a small lingering white head. Aromas of bread, earthiness, light citrus and light yeast. Palate was light bodied and smooth with a dry finish. Flavors of straw, light earthiness and light yeast with a smooth dry finish.

my favourite from the stop in at the brewpub, love unfiltered lagers! .. . hazy yellow .. great foam, it was in your face .. wheat, yeast, milkshake foam, husk, and lots of crisp straw .. really well done, i wanted more .. . . Im a cockney bitch, Im a ragamuffin from the streets!

GABF 2015. Kellerbier is a style I have been trying to understand since my travels in Germany. I liked this beer. Gold color and no head. Carbonation seems very low, a strong mineral quality, lager yeast and dry pilsner malt, sessionable, and enjoyable as a pilsner at least.

Short notes from GABF. Lightly hazed gold with a short head. Aroma impression is generic pale malt, saccharine, saltine crackers, green hops, grass, celery. Light bodied, sweet, under-carbonated and seemingly under-fermented, watery short finish with low relatively bitterness. Sadly this is nothing like true Franconian kellerbier.
Tap at the brewery. Golden colors. Nice white head. Grain, fresh baked bread, floral, soft. Nice feel, drinkable.
On tap at Prost Brewing. Pale gold with a good sized white head. Aroma Is of light skunk, herbal, grain, bread, and malty. Taste is of herbs, malt, nice noble hop character.
(Bue en fût sur place): Céréales coagulées, moelleuses et miellées avec une intégration brillante des houblons. Manque légèrement de finition mais on est très près de la Franconie.

On tap at brewery. Pours a cloudy yellow and makes a thin white head. Smells of bready yeast and good. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Gold pour, white head. Crisp beer, lightly hoppy, grainy. Nothing amazing here, but thats the beauty of this brewery. Simple and remarkably drinkable beers.

On tap at Prost. Golden and lightly hazy appearance with a white head and lacing. Mild aroma of noble hops, pale malts and light spices. Similar flavor, mild bitterness, light sweetness and a touch of spice. A little bland, but pretty clean and easy to drink, finishing dry.

On tap at the brewery. Pour is clear yellow with a frothy white head and great lacing. Grassy, doughy, lightly fruity, floral, cereal, somewhat grainy, and honey in the aroma. Taste is floral, fresh cut grass, biscuit, grain, fruity, bread, and dough with a clean bitter finish. Light body with high carbonation. Clean and easy to drink.

Mug at Prost. Cloudy light yellow with a tall white head. Serious pils aroma with tons of dough, crackers, grass, wood. Very clean and balanced and assertively hopped. Flavor is dry, clean, balanced. Lots of crackers, good grassy bite and a mouthfull of cereal. The finish is immaculate and dry.

Clear golden with a persistent small white head. Nose is surprisingly more grassier and floral than I expected, bringing a crisp hop bite and pale malt sweetness to the nose. Flavor is both clean and yeasty with a grainy biscuity blonde-ness, a bit of earthy sweetness, and a subtle crisp hop bite on the finish.

Tap at Prost - a buck fiddy more per glass than the regular pils - why? - anyway - just slightly hazy, with a pillowy head - drank side by side with the regular pils and didnt notice a significant difference - both were decently dry, with the same bitterness and crisp malt profile - this version had a bit more heft to it, and the light doughy/yeast character was fairly pleasant - like the regular pils, it is quite nice, but given the price difference, Ill be reaching for the regular pils next time.

Tap at Prost.  Pours hazy gold with a medium, frothy white head with medium retention and excellent lacing.  Aroma is Pils malt with spicy and earthy hops.  Flavor is malt dominant with medium hops and bitterness and a dry finish.  Medium body and carbonation.
